The '''feline''', usually short for '''cat or other feline''', is a [[monster class]] that appears in ''[[NetHack]]'', and is represented by the lowercase [[f]] glyph ({{white|f}}). Cats and felines are designated internally by the macro <code>'''S_FELINE'''</code>.{{refsrc|include/monsym.h|20|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}

The class contains the following monsters:{{refsrc|src/monst.c|347|version=NetHack 3.6.7}}

* {{monsymlink|kitten}}
* {{monsymlink|housecat}}
* {{monsymlink|jaguar}}
* {{monsymlink|lynx}}
* {{monsymlink|panther}}
* {{monsymlink|large cat}}
* {{monsymlink|tiger}}

{{upcoming|NetHack 3.7.0|The [[displacer beast]], {{monsym|displacer beast}}, is added to the monster class.}}

==Common traits==
Felines are quadrupedal and [[carnivorous]] [[animal]]s; they lack [[hands]], and are visible via [[infravision]]. Felines are all of [[neutral]] [[alignment]], and can be separated into two categories: 

* [[Domestic]] felines: the kitten, housecat and large cat
* Wild felines, or "big cats": the jaguar, lynx, panther, and tiger

Felines primarily attack via bites, and the wild felines also have claw attacks. [[Chatting]] to a tame domestic feline monster can be used to gauge its current condition.

Felines that eat [[mimic]] corpses may assume the form of a [[tripe ration]] for the duration of the meal if they do not assume a monster-specific form.{{refsrc|src/dogmove.c|1354|nethack=3.6.7}}

{{upcoming|3.7.0|All felines have [[infravision]].}}

===Generation===
Randomly generated felines that are not domestic are always created hostile; domestic felines are sometimes peaceful towards neutral characters.

==Strategy==
Most felines have high movement [[speed]], allowing them to deal surprising amounts of damage to an unprepared [[hero]] in the early game.

==History==
The feline monster class is introduced in [[NetHack 3.0.0]], which adds the kitten, housecat and large cat and moves the jaguar to the monster class. The jaguar first appears in Hack 1.21 (based on [[Jay Fenlason's Hack]]), where it uses the {{white|J}} glyph; from Hack for PDP-11 and [[Hack 1.0]] to [[NetHack 2.3e]], it uses the {{white|j}} glyph, and NetHack 3.0.0 gives the monster its current glyph.

The tiger is added to the monster class in [[NetHack 3.0.6]]. The panther originates in [[NetHack-- 3.1.3]], while the lynx originates in [[SLASH 6]], and both monsters make their vanilla debut in [[NetHack 3.3.0]].

==Variants==
===SLASH'EM===
[[SLASH'EM]] adds several monsters to the monster class:

* {{monsymlink|werepanther}}
* {{monsymlink|kamadan}}
* {{monsymlink|displacer beast}}
* {{monsymlink|caterwaul}}
* {{monsymlink|weretiger}}
* {{monsymlink|sabre-toothed cat}}
* {{monsymlink|hellcat}}

===UnNetHack===
In [[UnNetHack]], the feline is the second [[quest]] monster class for [[Cavepeople]], and makes up {{frac|6|175}} (3%) of the monsters randomly generated on the [[Caveman quest]].

===dNetHack===
[[dNetHack]], [[notdNetHack]] and [[notnotdNetHack]] add several monsters to the monster class:

* {{brightgreen|f}} [[Manticore (dNetHack)|manticore]]
* {{green|f}} [[serpent-necked lioness]]
* {{blue|f}} [[Displacer beast (dNetHack)|displacer beast]]
* {{yellow|f}} [[son of Typhon]]
* {{brightblue|f}} [[Hellcat (dNetHack)|hellcat]]
* {{orange|f}} [[Saber-toothed cat (dNetHack)|saber-toothed cat]]

The [[User:Chris/dNetHack/Cartouche of the Cat Lord|Cartouche of the Cat Lord]] is a [[Ward (dNetHack)|ward]] that can pacify hostile felines that see it, returning them to full health if successful. The [[User:Chris/dNetHack/Toustefna|Toustefna]] is a ward that can scare off felines.

===SpliceHack===
[[SpliceHack]] adds several monsters to the monster class:

* {{gray|f}} [[serval]]
* {{monsymlink|weretiger}}
* {{blue|f}} [[Serpopard (SpliceHack)|serpopard]]
* {{yellow|f}} [[lion]]
* {{white|f}} [[fat cat]]
* {{monsymlink|displacer beast}}
* {{monsymlink|hellcat}}

A [[pinch of catnip]] thrown at any feline will tame and [[confuse]] them, and a hero eating catnip while in the form of a feline will be confused for 2d8 (more) turns.

===EvilHack===
[[EvilHack]] adds two monsters to the monster class:

* {{yellow|f}} [[saber-toothed tiger]]
* {{monsymlink|displacer beast}}

===SlashTHEM===
[[SlashTHEM]] retains the monsters added in SLASH'EM, and adds two monsters to the monster class:

* {{yellow|f}} [[algolian suntiger]]
* {{yellow|f}} [[sphinx]]

The feline is the first quest monster class for [[Zookeeper]]s, and makes up {{frac|24|175}} (14%) of the monsters randomly generated on the [[Zookeeper quest]]. The feline is also the second quest monster class for Cavepeople as in UnNetHack, and makes up {{frac|6|175}} (3%) of the monsters randomly generated on the Caveman quest.

[[Liontamer]] is an [[artifact]] bullwhip that deals extra damage against felines.

===Hack'EM===
[[Hack'EM]] adds several monsters to the monster class, including many from other variants:

* {{gray|f}} [[serval]]
* {{monsymlink|caterwaul}}
* {{monsymlink|werepanther}}
* {{monsymlink|weretiger}}
* {{yellow|f}} [[Saber-toothed cat (Hack'EM)|saber-toothed cat]]
* {{yellow|f}} [[lion]]
* {{blue|f}} [[Serpopard (Hack'EM)|serpopard]]
* {{white|f}} [[fat cat]]
* {{monsymlink|kamadan}}
* {{yellow|f}} [[Saber-toothed tiger (Hack'EM)|saber-toothed tiger]]
* {{monsymlink|displacer beast}}
* {{monsymlink|hellcat}}

As in SpliceHack, a sprig of catnip thrown at any feline will tame and confuse them, and eating catnip while in the form of a feline will confuse the hero for 2d8 (more) turns.

